\f0\fs24 \cf0 # CLT Speed Race\
\
An interactive simulation illustrating the **speed of convergence in the Central Limit Theorem (CLT)** across different probability distributions.\
\
This project visualizes how quickly the standardized sample mean approaches the standard normal distribution depending on skewness, kurtosis, and tail behavior.\
\
---\
\
## Overview\
\
The classical CLT states that for i.i.d. random variables with finite mean and variance,\
\
Z_n = sqrt(n)(\uc0\u88 \u772 _n \u8722  \u956 ) / \u963   \u8594   N(0,1)\
\
However, the **rate of convergence** depends strongly on the underlying distribution.\
\
This notebook provides a simulation-based \'93speed race\'94 showing how fast the Gaussian approximation stabilizes.\
\
---\
\
## What the simulation shows\
\
For increasing sample sizes n:\
\
\'95 Histogram of standardized sample mean Z_n  \
\'95 Standard normal density overlay  \
\'95 Empirical CDF difference \uc0\u70 \u770 (x) \u8722  \u934 (x)  \
\'95 Kolmogorov\'96Smirnov distance  \
\
This allows direct comparison of convergence speed across distributions.\
\
---\
\
## Distributions included\
\
Normal \'97 baseline  \
Uniform \'97 very fast convergence  \
Exponential \'97 slower (skewed)  \
Laplace \'97 heavy tails  \
Student-t \'97 very slow for small df  \
Chi-square \'97 skewed  \
F \'97 heavy-tailed ratio  \
Lognormal \'97 strong skew  \
Pareto \'97 infinite variance if \uc0\u945  \u8804  2  \
Cauchy \'97 no CLT (variance undefined)\
\
